13Note that the term direct effect is well-defined only with respect to a certain model. Saying that changes in insulin levels X have a direct effect on glucose levels Y
might be a useful model for practicing physicians and patients suffering from diabetes. At the same time, this model excludes several chains of chemical reactions (i.e.,
molecular processes) that are involved in the transmission of changes in X to changes in the levels of Y. These intermediate chemical processes might be of interest to
biochemists or pharmacologists who develop a drug for patients suffering from diabetes. Thus, a direct effect of X on Y in the physician’s model will then be an indirect
effect (i.e., a mediated effect) in the biochemists’ model that explicitly includes chemical reactions as intermediate variables.
